ce:section.ce:para:
Lettuce (Lactuca sativa) and pepper (Capsicum annuum) plants of similar size were selected and transplanted into pots of uniform dimensions. These plants were chosen not because they belong to the same species, but to ensure that their initial size (biomass and overall plant dimensions) was roughly comparable. This selection criterion was crucial to allow for a fair assessment of the treatment's effects on growth parameters while accounting for their inherent physiological and developmental differences. The plants were divided into two groups and grown in the same climate, one group in a greenhouse (Fig. 1
                        ) and the other in a growing room (Fig. 2
                        ). All plants were irrigated four times a week with deionized water and regular fertilizer (50 mL) supplemented with the same amount of CDs for half of the plants within each group (1.9 mg/mL, 2 mL). The growth was followed for one month for the lettuce plants and two months for the pepper plants under natural sunlight. To ensure the accuracy of the NCDs effect, a variety of measurements were made including the growth rate (repeated thrice) [29,30], leaf number and area, fresh and dry weight of leaves, roots, and fruit (dried in a hot air oven at 45 °C for 72 h) and number of fruits.
